#Text=XXV
#Text=When the weather was dark and cloudy Edna could not work .
#Text=She needed the sun to mellow and temper her mood to the sticking point .
#Text=She had reached a stage when she seemed to be no longer feeling her way , working , when in the humor , with sureness and ease .
#Text=And being devoid of ambition , and striving not toward accomplishment , she drew satisfaction from the work in itself .
#Text=On rainy or melancholy days Edna went out and sought the society of the friends she had made at Grand Isle .
#Text=Or else she stayed indoors and nursed a mood with which she was becoming too familiar for her own comfort and peace of mind .
#Text=It was not despair ; but it seemed to her as if life were passing by , leaving its promise broken and unfulfilled .
#Text=Yet there were other days when she listened , was led on and deceived by fresh promises which her youth held out to her .
#Text=She went again to the races , and again .
#Text=Alcee Arobin and Mrs. Highcamp called for her one bright afternoon in Arobin 's drag .
#Text=Mrs. Highcamp was a worldly but unaffected , intelligent , slim , tall blonde woman in the forties , with an indifferent manner and blue eyes that stared .
#Text=She had a daughter who served her as a pretext for cultivating the society of young men of fashion .
#Text=Alcee Arobin was one of them .
#Text=He was a familiar figure at the race course , the opera , the fashionable clubs .
#Text=There was a perpetual smile in his eyes , which seldom failed to awaken a corresponding cheerfulness in any one who looked into them and listened to his good-humored voice .
#Text=His manner was quiet , and at times a little insolent .
#Text=He possessed a good figure , a pleasing face , not overburdened with depth of thought or feeling ; and his dress was that of the conventional man of fashion .
#Text=He admired Edna extravagantly , after meeting her at the races with her father .
#Text=He had met her before on other occasions , but she had seemed to him unapproachable until that day .
#Text=It was at his instigation that Mrs. Highcamp called to ask her to go with them to the Jockey Club to witness the turf event of the season .
#Text=There were possibly a few track men out there who knew the race horse as well as Edna , but there was certainly none who knew it better .
#Text=She sat between her two companions as one having authority to speak .
#Text=She laughed at Arobin 's pretensions , and deplored Mrs. Highcamp 's ignorance .
#Text=The race horse was a friend and intimate associate of her childhood .
#Text=The atmosphere of the stables and the breath of the blue grass paddock revived in her memory and lingered in her nostrils .
#Text=She did not perceive that she was talking like her father as the sleek geldings ambled in review before them .
#Text=She played for very high stakes , and fortune favored her .
#Text=The fever of the game flamed in her cheeks and eyes , and it got into her blood and into her brain like an intoxicant .
#Text=People turned their heads to look at her , and more than one lent an attentive ear to her utterances , hoping thereby to secure the elusive but ever-desired “ tip . ”
#Text=Arobin caught the contagion of excitement which drew him to Edna like a magnet .
#Text=Mrs. Highcamp remained , as usual , unmoved , with her indifferent stare and uplifted eyebrows .
#Text=Edna stayed and dined with Mrs. Highcamp upon being urged to do so .
#Text=Arobin also remained and sent away his drag .
#Text=The dinner was quiet and uninteresting , save for the cheerful efforts of Arobin to enliven things .
#Text=Mrs. Highcamp deplored the absence of her daughter from the races , and tried to convey to her what she had missed by going to the “ Dante reading ” instead of joining them .
#Text=The girl held a geranium leaf up to her nose and said nothing , but looked knowing and noncommittal .
#Text=Mr. Highcamp was a plain , bald-headed man , who only talked under compulsion .
#Text=He was unresponsive .
#Text=Mrs. Highcamp was full of delicate courtesy and consideration toward her husband .
#Text=She addressed most of her conversation to him at table .
#Text=They sat in the library after dinner and read the evening papers together under the droplight ; while the younger people went into the drawing-room near by and talked .
#Text=Miss Highcamp played some selections from Grieg upon the piano .
#Text=She seemed to have apprehended all of the composer 's coldness and none of his poetry .
#Text=While Edna listened she could not help wondering if she had lost her taste for music .
#Text=When the time came for her to go home , Mr. Highcamp grunted a lame offer to escort her , looking down at his slippered feet with tactless concern .
#Text=It was Arobin who took her home .
#Text=The car ride was long , and it was late when they reached Esplanade Street .
#Text=Arobin asked permission to enter for a second to light his cigarette -- his match safe was empty .
#Text=He filled his match safe , but did not light his cigarette until he left her , after she had expressed her willingness to go to the races with him again .
#Text=Edna was neither tired nor sleepy .
#Text=She was hungry again , for the Highcamp dinner , though of excellent quality , had lacked abundance .
#Text=She rummaged in the larder and brought forth a slice of Gruyere and some crackers .
#Text=She opened a bottle of beer which she found in the icebox .
#Text=Edna felt extremely restless and excited .
#Text=She vacantly hummed a fantastic tune as she poked at the wood embers on the hearth and munched a cracker .
